        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe HCN and HCO+ in NGC 3256 in a single pointing centered on the galaxy. 

Imaging requirements:

We require an angular resolution of 1" (~170 pc) to match the spatial scale of our ALMA Cycle 1 programme to observe the same dense gas tracers in the Antennae (1.6").  In addition, we can degrade the resolution slightly to match the resolution of the ALMA Cycle 0 observations of CO J=1-0 in NGC 3256 (PI: Sakamoto).  At this resolution, we will resolve many of the super giant molecular complexes in NGC 3256. We do not require the Atacama Compact Array as the dense gas structure in NGC 3256 will be relatively compact (&lt;10"). 


Correlator setup:

We will use band 3 to observe both HCN and HCO+ in NGC 3256 concurrently, along with the continuum. In the lower sideband, we will place three spectral windows across the two basebands. In the first baseband, our spectral windows will be placed at 88.6316 GHz and 89.1885 GHz, centered on HCN J=1-0 and HCO+ J=1-0 respectively, each with a bandwidth of 937.5 MHz (3181 km/s), and a spectral resolution of 1.938 Mhz (6.6 km/s). In the ALMA CO J=1-0 observations, the CO J=1-0 emission spans about 400 km/s across the entire galaxy. Both lines should lie well within their respective spectral windows. In the second baseband, we will place a spectral window at 90.66356 GHz with a bandwidth of 1875 MHz (6258 km/s) and a spectral resolution of 1.938 MHz (6.470 km/s). We will use this spectral window to search for HNC J=1-0 emission, which also traces dense gas. In the upper sideband, our spectral windows will be placed at 100.5 GHz and 102.4 GHz with a bandwidth of 2000 MHz (5646 km/s) and a spectral resolution of 31.25 MHz (94.092 km/s), to study the free-free emission from within NGC 3256.


Requested sensitivity:

Our desired sensitivity per pointing for HCN and HCO+ is 60 mK (0.38 mJy) with a frequency width of 10 km/s. Assuming a representative frequency of 88.6316 GHz, these observations would take a total of 2.99 hours for the single pointing (5.41 hours including calibrators). The peak CO J=1-0 emission in the ALMA Cycle 1 program  (PI: Sakamoto) is ~10 K (~0.4 Jy/beam) in a 3" x 1.4" beam and corresponds to the southern nucleus. The northern nucleus' peak emission is ~7 K. Assuming a CO/HCN ratio of 10 in units of K km/s, and that CO and HCN are cospatial, we would detect the HCN peak in the souther and northern nuclei with signal-to-noise ratios of 17 and 12 respectively. Furthermore, we should detect all of the molecualr gas in the inner 4 kpc diameter (see Figure 1 top and middle left of our proposal) to at least 5 sigma. In addition, with such a high sensitivity, we will be able to study the 3 dimensional distribution of the molecular gas by looking along the velocity axis of our cube. 
The 2 basebands not used to observe HCN, HCO+ or HNC will be used to map the free-free continuum emission across NGC 3256, each containing one spectral window. We do not expect to detect any spectral lines within these two spectral windows.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
